'''Gaseous mediators''' are [[chemicals]] that are produced in small amounts by some [[cell (biology)|cell]]s of the [[mammal]]ian body and have a number of biological signalling functions. There are three so-far-identified gaseous mediator molecules: [[nitric oxide]] (NO), [[hydrogen sulfide]] (H<sub>2</sub>S), and [[carbon monoxide]] (CO).<ref>{{cite journal|pmc=1363746 | pmid=16467393 | doi=10.1152/japplphysiol.00793.2005 | volume=100 | issue=3 | title=Carbon monoxide and hydrogen sulfide: gaseous messengers in cerebrovascular circulation |date=March 2006 | journal=J. Appl. Physiol. | pages=1065–76| author1=Leffler | first1=C. W. | last2=Parfenova | first2=H | last3=Jaggar | first3=J. H. | last4=Wang | first4=R }}</ref>

